      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks, that makes sense. using a vector is definitely safer. \n\nbut honestly, it was kind of hard to see why it was happening just by looking at the logic. why does the memory just stay there? like, once the loop iteration is over and the pointer variable `txAmount` goes out of scope, why doesn't the system just automatically reclaim that memory? it feels like something is just quietly eating up the resources in the background.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In C++, memory management is explicit, which is why you aren't automatically freed when you go out of scope. When you allocate memory, you're responsible for deallocating it. The system does not automatically reclaim unused memory. This is a design choice of C++ to give the programmer more control over memory, allowing more complex, fine-grained memory management. This is good for performance because you can direct when and how memory is freed, avoiding any automatic reclaim processes that could introduce overhead.\n\nHowever, this same granularity comes with the responsibility of keeping track of every memory allocation and deallocation. A failure to correctly deallocate fixed resource durations like those encapsulated by `new` and `delete` can lead to memory leaks. This is similar to not cleaning up your workspace timing after finishing a job; things won't disappear by themselves; you have to do it. Modern C++ provides high-level objects like `vector`, `list`, `map`, etc., which abstract these memory management responsibilities with the promise of ensuring proper cleanup, making code safer and often more readable in the process.\n\nIn simpler terms, just as all the things you used for a task and didn't plan to get rid of automatically go away unless you store them away first, similarly, in",
      "source": "target",
